\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Amanita ocreata
\f1\i0 , commonly known as the 
\f2\b death angel
\f1\b0 , 
\f2\b destroying angel
\f1\b0 , 
\f2\b angel of death
\f1\b0  or more precisely 
\f2\b western North American destroying angel
\f1\b0 , is a deadly {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poison"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 poisonous}} {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basidiomycete"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 basidiomycete}} {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fungus"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 fungus}}, one of many in the genus {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amanita"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\i \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Amanita}}. Occurring in the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pacific_Northwest"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Pacific Northwest}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/California_floristic_province"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 California floristic provinces}} of North America, 
\f0\i A. ocreata
\f1\i0  {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mycorrhiza"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 associates}} with {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oak"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 oak}} trees. The large fruiting bodies (the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mushroom"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 mushrooms}}) generally appear in spring; the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pileus_(mycology)"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 cap}} may be white or ochre and often develops a brownish centre, while the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stipe_(mycology)"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 stipe}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Annulus_(mycology)"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 ring}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lamella_(mycology)"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 gill}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volva_(mycology)"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 volva}} are all white. \

\f0\i Amanita ocreata
\f1\i0  resemble several edible species commonly consumed by humans, increasing the risk of accidental poisoning. Mature fruiting bodies can be confused with the edible {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amanita_velosa"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\i \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 A. velosa}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amanita_lanei"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\i \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 A. lanei}} or {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volvopluteus_gloiocephalus"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\i \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Volvopluteus gloiocephalus}}, while immature specimens may be difficult to distinguish from edible {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agaricus"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\i \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Agaricus}} mushrooms or puffballs. Similar in toxicity to the death cap ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amanita_phalloides"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\i \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 A. phalloides}}) and destroying angels of Europe ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amanita_virosa"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\i \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 A. virosa}}) and eastern North America ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amanita_bisporigera"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\i \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 A. bisporigera}}), it is a potentially deadly fungus responsible for several poisonings in California.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amanita_ocreata#cite_note-Amth77-1"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 [1]}} Its principal toxic constituent, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%CE%91-amanitin"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 \uc0\u945 -amanitin}}, damages the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liver"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 liver}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kidney"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 kidneys}}, often fatally, and has no known antidote, though silybin and N-acetylcysteine show promise.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amanita_ocreata#cite_note-Enjalbert-2"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 [2]}} The initial symptoms are {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gastrointestinal"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 gastrointestinal}} and include abdominal pain, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diarrhea"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 diarrhea}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vomiting"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 vomiting}}. These subside temporarily after 2\'963\'a0days, though ongoing damage to internal organs during this time is common; symptoms of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jaundice"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 jaundice}}, diarrhea, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Delirium"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 delirium}}, seizures, and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coma"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 coma}} may follow with death from liver failure 6\'9616\'a0days post ingestion. \
